name: Frame
comment: A single stack frame. Each frame points to a precise location in Dart code.

uri.name: uri
uri.comment:
The URI of the file in which the code is located.

This URI will usually have the scheme dart, file, http, or https.

line.name: line
line.comment:
The line number on which the code location is located.

This can be null, indicating that the line number is unknown or unimportant.

column.name: column
column.comment:
The column number of the code location.

This can be null, indicating that the column number is unknown or unimportant.

member.name: member
member.comment:
The name of the member in which the code location occurs.

Anonymous closures are represented as <fn> in this member string.

isCore.name: isCore
isCore.comment: Whether this stack frame comes from the Dart core libraries.

library.name: library
library.comment:
Returns a human-friendly description of the library that this stack frame comes from.

This will usually be the string form of stack_trace/stack_trace.Frame.uri, but a relative URI will be used if possible.

package.name: package
package.comment: Returns the name of the package this stack frame comes from, or null if this stack frame doesn't come from a package: URL.

location.name: location
location.comment: A human-friendly description of the code location.

caller.name: caller
caller.comment:
Returns a single frame of the current stack.

By default, this will return the frame above the current method. If stack_trace/stack_trace.Frame.Frame-caller.level is 0, it will return the current method's frame; if stack_trace/stack_trace.Frame.Frame-caller.level is higher than 1, it will return higher frames.

parseVM.name: parseVM
parseVM.comment: Parses a string representation of a Dart VM stack frame.

parseV8.name: parseV8
parseV8.comment: Parses a string representation of a Chrome/V8 stack frame.

parseIE.name: parseIE
parseIE.comment:
Parses a string representation of an IE stack frame.

IE10+ frames look just like V8 frames. Prior to IE10, stack traces can't be retrieved.

parseFirefox.name: parseFirefox
parseFirefox.comment: Parses a string representation of a Firefox stack frame.

parseSafari6_0.name: parseSafari6_0
parseSafari6_0.comment:
Parses a string representation of a Safari 6.0 stack frame.

Safari 6.0 frames look just like Firefox frames. Prior to Safari 6.0, stack traces can't be retrieved.

parseSafari6_1.name: parseSafari6_1
parseSafari6_1.comment: Parses a string representation of a Safari 6.1+ stack frame.

parseFriendly.name: parseFriendly
parseFriendly.comment: Parses this package's string representation of a stack frame.

toString.name: toString
toString.comment: Returns a string representation of this object.

hashCode.name: hashCode
hashCode.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality operator ==. Other than that there are no guarantees about the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides stack_trace/stack_trace.Frame.hashCode it should override the equality operator as well to maintain consistency.

runtimeType.name: runtimeType
runtimeType.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.

==.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all dart-core.Objects is to return true if and only if this and stack_trace/stack_trace.Frame.==.other are the same object.

Override this method to specify a different equality relation on a class. The overriding method must still be an equivalence relation. That is, it must be:

  • Total: It must return a boolean for all arguments. It should never throw or return null.

  • Reflexive: For all objects o, o == o must be true.

  • Symmetric: For all objects o1 and o2, o1 == o2 and o2 == o1 must either both be true, or both be false.

  • Transitive: For all objects o1, o2, and o3, if o1 == o2 and o2 == o3 are true, then o1 == o3 must be true.

The method should also be consistent over time, so equality of two objects should not change over time, or at least only change if one of the objects was modified.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override the stack_trace/stack_trace.Frame.hashCode method as well to maintain consistency.

toString.name: toString
toString.comment: Returns a string representation of this object.

noSuchMethod.name: noSuchMethod
noSuchMethod.comment:
stack_trace/stack_trace.Frame.noSuchMethod is invoked when users invoke a non-existent method on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the invocation are passed to stack_trace/stack_trace.Frame.noSuchMethod in an dart-core.Invocation. If stack_trace/stack_trace.Frame.noSuchMethod returns a value, that value becomes the result of the original invocation.

The default behavior of stack_trace/stack_trace.Frame.noSuchMethod is to throw a dart-core.NoSuchMethodError.
